{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17618838","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17618838"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:25:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:25:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16517"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16517","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16517"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9208"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75398"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9208","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9208"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16517"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60907"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7141"},{"type":"tags","id":"10337"},{"type":"tags","id":"10350"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21836"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21840"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75398","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75398"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe descending motor pathways of the central nervous system are organised into lateral and medial divisions. These pathways control different aspects of movement and posture.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following descending motor tracts originates in the brainstem and belongs to the lateral division?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tectospinal tract","Reticulospinal tract","Lateral corticospinal tract","Rubrospinal tract","Vestibulospinal tract"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe descending motor pathways are organised into lateral and medial divisions based on their anatomical location and functional roles. The \u003Cstrong\u003Erubrospinal tract\u003C/strong\u003E originates in the red nucleus of the midbrain and is part of the lateral division. It is important in the control of distal limb movements, particularly in the upper limb.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elateral corticospinal tract\u003C/strong\u003E, while also part of the lateral division, originates in the cerebral cortex rather than the brainstem. It is the primary pathway for voluntary control of skilled movements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etectospinal tract\u003C/strong\u003E originates in the superior colliculus of the midbrain and belongs to the medial division. It is involved in coordinating head and neck movements in response to visual stimuli.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ereticulospinal tract\u003C/strong\u003E originates in the reticular formation of the brainstem and belongs to the medial division. It plays a role in posture, balance, and automatic movements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Evestibulospinal tract\u003C/strong\u003E originates in the vestibular nuclei of the brainstem and belongs to the medial division. It is important for maintaining balance and posture in response to head movements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe lateral division generally controls fine, discrete movements of the distal limbs, while the medial division controls gross movements, posture, and balance of axial and proximal muscles.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The rubrospinal tract originates in the red nucleus of the midbrain and is part of the lateral division of the descending motor pathways.","The lateral division of descending motor pathways includes the rubrospinal and lateral corticospinal tracts, which primarily control distal limb movements.","The medial division includes the tectospinal, reticulospinal, and vestibulospinal tracts, which primarily control axial and proximal limb movements."],"references":["Olivares-Moreno R, Rodriguez-Moreno P, Lopez-Virgen V, Mac\u00edas M, Altamira-Camacho M, Rojas-Piloni G. Corticospinal vs Rubrospinal Revisited: An Evolutionary Perspective for Sensorimotor Integration. Front Neurosci. 2021 Jun 11;15:686481. doi: 10.3389/fnins.2021.686481. PMID: 34177458; PMCID: PMC8226017.","R\u00fcber T, Schlaug G, Lindenberg R. Compensatory role of the cortico-rubro-spinal tract in motor recovery after stroke. Neurology. 2012 Aug 7;79(6):515-22. doi: 10.1212/WNL.0b013e31826356e8. Epub 2012 Jul 25. PMID: 22843266; PMCID: PMC3413760.","Hall, J. E., \u0026 Hall, M. E. (2020). Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book: Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60907"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16517"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60907","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60907"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-29T19:26:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-29T19:33:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9208"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75398"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationsh